V, 149, tenuis euim oratura deum longeque remota sensibus a nostris animi aix meute videtur. But we must not neglect the difference of ais et ua· tura deorum and tenuis natura deum. The latter, on account of the epithet tenuis, can only he understood of the divine quasi corpus which the mind perceives, because in virtue of its possessing the same tenuitas it is in immediate contact with and directly affected by it; the vis et natura deorum is something more than this quasi corporeality, and denotes the whole onter and inner constitution upon which the vitae actio and the mentis agitatio (ξ 45 ff), virtue, wisdom‚ happiness and immortality of the gods depend. If in the passage under discussion we are to under· stand simply the corporeality of the gods, of which we are cognizant by mere perception, Cicero could not have written cernatur, which would only admit vis et natura for its subject, but cernantur, sc. di, which 1 (Prof. Sch.) have therefore restored. The perceptible tenuitas of the gods, although not the same as their ais et notura, still isa part of it, is one side of their being, and may therefore as depending upon this be designated by ut ‚· it lies in the nature of the gods that their corporeality as well should ¹be perceivable only hy the meus, and not by the senses. ln the Greek original which Cicero used there was probably an infinitive depending on bare, perhaps γιγνώσκεσθαι, which could be rendered in Latin by the singu· ὁ laras well as by the plural of the finite verb. Thus Cotta in his reply (ξ 105) takes the proposition as applicahle only to the corporeality and not to the collective being of the gods, and speaks of the speciem dei be· cause this alone in the gods is what we immediately perceive, quod mente cernitur.
